lines.text: well, i was born a coal miner's daughter
in a cabin on a hill in butcher holler
we were poor but we had love.
that's the one thing-that daddy made sure of
he shoveled coal to make a poor man's dollar
my daddy worked all night in-the van-leer coal mine
all day long in-a field a-hoein' corn
mommy rocked the babies at night
and read-the bible by-the coal oil light
and everything would start- all over come break of morrn'
daddy loved and-raised eight kids on a miner's pay
mommy-scrubbed our-coats on-a washboard every day.
well,-i seen her fingers bleed,-
to complain there was no need.
she's smile in- mommy's understanding way
in-the summer time we didn't have shoes to wear.
but-in the-winter time we'd all-get a-brand new pair
from a-mail-order catalogue,
money made from selling a hog.
daddy always managed to-get the money somewhere
yeah,-i'm proud -to-be to-be a coal miner's daughter.
i-remember-well the-well the-well-where i drew water
the work we done was hard,-
at-night we'd sleep cause we were tired.
i never thought of ever leaving butcher hol ler.
well,-a lot of-things have changed since way back then.
and it's so- good to-be back ho me-again
